1
00:00:02,085 --> 00:00:07,090
Salutations. This is Sally Calypso
with the traffic news at 70:175.

2
00:00:07,216 --> 00:00:11,845
We've got reports of
a multiple stack-pile at Junction 509,

3
00:00:11,929 --> 00:00:15,390
with a spate of carjackings reported
on New 5th Avenue.

4
00:00:15,474 --> 00:00:18,602
So you take care now. Drive safely.

5
00:00:19,394 --> 00:00:21,522
(CRASHING)

6
00:00:23,065 --> 00:00:26,235
They're gonna get in.
There's no stopping them.

7
00:00:27,819 --> 00:00:31,198
The police are on their way, I promise.
I've sounded the alarm.

8
00:00:31,281 --> 00:00:34,243
Repeat, this is car 1-0-Hawk-5.

9
00:00:34,326 --> 00:00:36,495
We have a problem,
require urgent assistance.

10
00:00:36,620 --> 00:00:39,373
OPERATOR: Thank you for your call.
You have been placed on hold.

11
00:00:39,456 --> 00:00:40,624
It's all your fault.

12
00:00:40,707 --> 00:00:43,293
You lied to the computer.
You said there were three of us.

13
00:00:43,377 --> 00:00:45,504
You told them three!

14
00:00:45,629 --> 00:00:49,132
Repeat, urgent assistance.
Car 1-0-Hawk-5.

15
00:00:49,216 --> 00:00:51,510
This is an emergency. Help us!

16
00:00:51,593 --> 00:00:54,054
Oh, my God, I'm begging you!
Please, help us!

17
00:00:57,808 --> 00:01:02,938
The weather is at 36 degrees,
and it's smooth skies all the way home.

18
00:01:03,021 --> 00:01:06,525
This is Sally Calypso signing off.
Missing you already.

19
00:01:07,025 --> 00:01:09,111
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

20
00:01:43,729 --> 00:01:47,774
Just one trip, that's what I said.
One trip in the Tardis and then home.

21
00:01:47,858 --> 00:01:52,654
Although, I suppose we could
stretch the definition.

22
00:01:52,738 --> 00:01:55,324
Take one trip into the past,
one trip into the future.

23
00:01:55,407 --> 00:01:58,368
-How do you fancy that?
-No complaints from me!

24
00:01:58,452 --> 00:02:01,872
How about a different planet?

25
00:02:01,955 --> 00:02:04,124
Can we go to yours?

26
00:02:05,667 --> 00:02:07,669
No, there's plenty of other places.

27
00:02:07,753 --> 00:02:10,297
Come on.
I mean, the planet of the Time Lords.

28
00:02:10,380 --> 00:02:13,383
That's got to be worth a look.
What's it like?

29
00:02:13,467 --> 00:02:15,427
It's beautiful, yeah.

30
00:02:15,510 --> 00:02:19,973
Is it like, you know, outer space
cities, all spires and stuff?

31
00:02:20,057 --> 00:02:21,350
I suppose it is.

32
00:02:21,433 --> 00:02:24,186
Great big temples and cathedrals?

33
00:02:24,686 --> 00:02:25,771
Yeah.

34
00:02:25,854 --> 00:02:28,065
Lots of planets in the sky?

35
00:02:30,025 --> 00:02:32,152
The sky's a burnt orange.

36
00:02:33,904 --> 00:02:37,115
With a citadel enclosed
in a mighty glass dome,

37
00:02:38,283 --> 00:02:40,535
shining under the twin suns.

38
00:02:41,161 --> 00:02:43,580
Beyond that,
the mountains go on forever.

39
00:02:43,664 --> 00:02:46,667
Slopes of deep red grass,

40
00:02:47,751 --> 00:02:49,461
capped with snow.

41
00:02:53,882 --> 00:02:55,550
Can we go there?

42
00:02:57,678 --> 00:03:00,180
Nah! Where's the fun for me?
I don't want to go home.

43
00:03:00,263 --> 00:03:01,682
Instead...

44
00:03:04,184 --> 00:03:08,313
This is much better.
Year 5000000053. Planet New Earth.

45
00:03:08,397 --> 00:03:11,608
Second home of mankind.
50,000 light years from your old world,

46
00:03:11,692 --> 00:03:14,111
and we're slap-bang in the middle
of New New York.

47
00:03:14,236 --> 00:03:16,405
Although, technically,
it's 15 New Yorks since the original,

48
00:03:16,488 --> 00:03:19,950
so it's New New New New New New New New
New New New New New New New New York.

49
00:03:20,117 --> 00:03:22,285
One of the most dazzling cities
ever built.

50
00:03:22,369 --> 00:03:24,454
Oh, that's nice.

51
00:03:24,538 --> 00:03:26,790
A Time Lord version of dazzling!

52
00:03:26,873 --> 00:03:31,002
A bit of rain never hurt anyone.
Come on, let's get under cover.

53
00:03:35,215 --> 00:03:37,134
He has arrived.

54
00:03:37,217 --> 00:03:38,844
What should I do?

55
00:03:38,927 --> 00:03:42,305
Find him before it's too late.

56
00:03:50,856 --> 00:03:54,526
Well, it looks like the same old Earth
to me, on a Wednesday afternoon.

57
00:03:54,609 --> 00:03:56,695
Hold on, hold on, let's have a look.

58
00:04:00,365 --> 00:04:01,992
(POUNDING)

59
00:04:02,075 --> 00:04:04,411
...and the driving should be
clear and easy,

60
00:04:04,494 --> 00:04:08,373
with 15 extra lanes open for
the New New Jersey Expressway.

61
00:04:08,915 --> 00:04:11,001
That's more like it!
That's the view we had last time.

62
00:04:11,376 --> 00:04:13,378
This must be the lower levels.

63
00:04:13,462 --> 00:04:15,839
Down at the base of the tower.
Some sort of under city.

64
00:04:15,922 --> 00:04:17,924
You've brought me to the slums?

65
00:04:18,008 --> 00:04:20,761
Much more interesting.
It's all cocktails and glitter up there.

66
00:04:20,844 --> 00:04:23,472
-This is the real city.
-You'd enjoy anything.

67
00:04:23,555 --> 00:04:27,476
That's me. Ah, the rain's stopping.
Better and better!

68
00:04:27,559 --> 00:04:31,438
When you say last time,
was that you and Rose?

69
00:04:31,521 --> 00:04:34,399
Um, yeah. Yeah, it was. Yeah.

70
00:04:34,483 --> 00:04:36,818
You're taking me to the same planets
that you took her?

71
00:04:36,902 --> 00:04:38,779
What's wrong with that?

72
00:04:38,862 --> 00:04:42,032
Nothing. Just ever heard
the word "rebound”?

73
00:04:43,033 --> 00:04:46,244
Oh, you should have said!
How long have you been there?

74
00:04:46,369 --> 00:04:48,830
Happy. You want happy. Happy!

75
00:04:48,914 --> 00:04:52,209
Customers, customers!
We've got customers!

76
00:04:52,292 --> 00:04:53,418
We have business.

77
00:04:53,543 --> 00:04:55,212
(WOMAN SHOUTING)

78
00:04:55,337 --> 00:04:57,005
Happy, happy, lovely happy!

79
00:04:57,088 --> 00:04:58,799
Anger. Buy some anger!

80
00:04:58,882 --> 00:05:02,010
It's mellow, makes you feel
all bendy and soft all day long.

81
00:05:02,093 --> 00:05:05,055
Don't go to them, they'll rip you off.
Do you want some happy?

82
00:05:05,138 --> 00:05:08,809
-No, thanks.
-Are they selling drugs?

83
00:05:08,892 --> 00:05:11,102
I think they're selling moods.

84
00:05:11,186 --> 00:05:13,063
Same thing, isn't it?

85
00:05:13,855 --> 00:05:17,526
-WOMAN: Over here, sweetheart!
-Hey, you, over here! Over here!

86
00:05:17,609 --> 00:05:20,487
Come over here, yeah.
And what can I get you, my love?

87
00:05:20,612 --> 00:05:23,240
-I want to buy forget.
-I've got forget, my darling.

88
00:05:23,323 --> 00:05:25,826
What strength?
How much do you want forgetting?

89
00:05:25,909 --> 00:05:28,870
It's my mother and father.
They went on the motorway.

90
00:05:28,954 --> 00:05:31,081
Oh, that's a swine.

91
00:05:32,165 --> 00:05:35,585
Try this. Forget 43. That's 2 credits.

92
00:05:35,669 --> 00:05:39,089
Sorry, but hold on a minute.
What happened to your parents?

93
00:05:39,172 --> 00:05:43,635
-They drove off.
-Yeah, but they might drive back.

94
00:05:43,718 --> 00:05:46,346
Everyone goes to the motorway
in the end.

95
00:05:46,429 --> 00:05:48,431
I've lost them.

96
00:05:48,515 --> 00:05:51,852
But they can't have gone far.
You could find them.

97
00:05:52,894 --> 00:05:54,604
No. No, no, don't!

98
00:05:58,358 --> 00:06:01,278
-I'm sorry, what were you saying?
-Your parents.

99
00:06:01,361 --> 00:06:03,864
Your mother and father.
They're on the motorway.

100
00:06:03,947 --> 00:06:05,282
Are they?

101
00:06:06,116 --> 00:06:07,868
That's nice.

102
00:06:08,952 --> 00:06:11,204
I'm sorry, I won't keep you.

103
00:06:15,333 --> 00:06:18,461
So that's the human race
five billion years in the future?

104
00:06:18,545 --> 00:06:20,797
Off their heads on chemicals.

105
00:06:20,881 --> 00:06:23,592
Sorry. I'm really sorry.
We just need three, that's all.

106
00:06:23,675 --> 00:06:26,428
-Let her go! I'm warning you!
-It's not our fault!

107
00:06:26,511 --> 00:06:29,055
Whatever you want, I can help.
We can help.

108
00:06:29,139 --> 00:06:31,933
-But first you've got to let her go!
-Sorry.

109
00:06:32,017 --> 00:06:33,643
(DOOR SLAMS)

110
00:06:39,649 --> 00:06:40,984
(BUZZING)

111
00:06:42,652 --> 00:06:46,531
The Doctor is so gonna kill you. Never
mind him, I'm gonna kill you myself!

112
00:06:46,656 --> 00:06:49,117
-Let go of me!
-Give her some sleep.

113
00:06:49,200 --> 00:06:51,036
Don't you dare! Don't put that near me.

114
00:06:51,119 --> 00:06:54,456
It's just sleep. It won't do you
any harm if you don't fight it.

115
00:06:54,539 --> 00:06:57,000
That's it, come on. That's it.

116
00:06:57,125 --> 00:06:58,710
Get on board.

117
00:07:05,342 --> 00:07:07,844
Engaging antigravs. Hold on.

118
00:07:14,559 --> 00:07:16,728
Martha!

119
00:07:22,859 --> 00:07:25,737
She's all right, she's breathing.
Pulse is fine.

120
00:07:25,862 --> 00:07:27,572
No harm done.

121
00:07:27,697 --> 00:07:30,408
She looks rich. She must have got lost.

122
00:07:30,533 --> 00:07:32,953
Well, she's worth
her weight in gold to us.

123
00:07:33,036 --> 00:07:37,457
This is car 4-6-5-Diamond-6.
We have three passengers, repeat, three.

124
00:07:37,540 --> 00:07:40,919
-Request access to the fast lane.
-Access granted.

125
00:07:41,044 --> 00:07:42,337
Oh, yes.

126
00:07:48,551 --> 00:07:51,721
I thought you'd come back.
Do you want some happy-happy?

127
00:07:51,805 --> 00:07:54,224
Those people, who were they?
Where did they take her?

128
00:07:54,307 --> 00:07:56,434
They've taken her to the motorway.

129
00:07:56,559 --> 00:07:58,353
Looked like carjackers to me.

130
00:07:58,436 --> 00:08:01,815
I'd give up now, darling.
You won't see her again.

131
00:08:01,898 --> 00:08:04,985
Used to be thriving, this place.
You couldn't move.

132
00:08:05,068 --> 00:08:06,736
But they all go to the motorway
in the end.

133
00:08:06,861 --> 00:08:09,364
He kept on saying three, we need three.
What did he mean, three?

134
00:08:09,447 --> 00:08:12,158
It's the car-sharing policy,
to save fuel.

135
00:08:12,242 --> 00:08:15,036
You get special access
if you're carrying three adults.

136
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:16,287
This motorway, how do I get there?

137
00:08:16,287 --> 00:08:16,705
This motorway, how do I get there?

138
00:08:16,788 --> 00:08:19,874
Straight down the alley, keep going
to the end. You cannae miss it.

139
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:24,295
Tell you what, buy some happy-happy.
Then you'll be smiling, my love.

140
00:08:24,379 --> 00:08:26,339
A word of advice to all of you.

141
00:08:26,423 --> 00:08:29,342
Cash up, close down and pack your bags.

142
00:08:29,426 --> 00:08:30,969
Why is that, then?

143
00:08:31,052 --> 00:08:33,555
Because as soon as
I've found her alive and well,

144
00:08:33,680 --> 00:08:36,850
and I will find her alive and well,
then I'm coming back.

145
00:08:36,933 --> 00:08:40,061
And this street is closing. Tonight!

146
00:08:46,109 --> 00:08:48,695
(DISTANT VOICES)

147
00:08:50,155 --> 00:08:53,825
MAN: Now you just settle back.
It's all gonna be worth it.

148
00:08:55,410 --> 00:08:58,121
WOMAN: ...the view from the windows,

149
00:08:58,246 --> 00:09:00,790
you can see all the way out to the...

150
00:09:00,874 --> 00:09:05,211
Open sky. They say the air smells
like apple grass. Can you imagine?

151
00:09:05,295 --> 00:09:07,172
MAN: The houses are made of wood.

152
00:09:07,297 --> 00:09:10,884
There are jobs going in the foundries.
Everyone says so.

153
00:09:10,967 --> 00:09:14,637
Take me back. Whoever you are,
just take me back to my friend.

154
00:09:14,721 --> 00:09:17,974
That's all I want. I won't cause
any trouble, just take me back.

155
00:09:18,058 --> 00:09:20,769
I'm sorry. That's not a real gun.

156
00:09:21,603 --> 00:09:25,148
-Well, you would say that.
-Where do you get a gun from these days?

157
00:09:25,231 --> 00:09:27,609
I wouldn't even know how to fire.

158
00:09:27,692 --> 00:09:29,319
No, nor me.

159
00:09:30,028 --> 00:09:31,362
Okay.

160
00:09:31,446 --> 00:09:33,156
What's your name?

161
00:09:33,281 --> 00:09:35,825
Martha. Martha Jones.

162
00:09:35,909 --> 00:09:38,495
Well, I'm Cheen and this is Milo.

163
00:09:38,578 --> 00:09:41,664
And I swear, we're sorry.
We're really, really sorry.

164
00:09:41,748 --> 00:09:44,667
We just needed access to the fast lane,
but I promise as soon as we arrive,

165
00:09:44,751 --> 00:09:46,836
we'll drop you off, and you can go back
and find your friend.

166
00:09:47,003 --> 00:09:50,840
-Seriously?
-I swear. Look, honesty patch.

167
00:09:51,674 --> 00:09:56,179
All the same, it's still kidnapping.
Where are we anyway?

168
00:09:56,262 --> 00:09:58,973
-We're on the motorway.
-What's that then, fog?

169
00:09:59,057 --> 00:10:00,558
It's exhaust fumes.

170
00:10:00,642 --> 00:10:03,645
We're going out to Brooklyn. Everyone
says the air is so much cleaner.

171
00:10:03,728 --> 00:10:05,897
And we couldn't stay
at Pharmacy Town because...

172
00:10:05,980 --> 00:10:08,608
Well, "cause of me. I'm pregnant.

173
00:10:08,691 --> 00:10:12,403
We only discovered it last week.
Scan says it's gonna be a boy.

174
00:10:12,487 --> 00:10:15,698
Right. What do I do now,
congratulate my kidnappers?

175
00:10:15,782 --> 00:10:19,285
We're not kidnappers. Not really.

176
00:10:19,369 --> 00:10:21,454
No! You're idiots!

177
00:10:21,538 --> 00:10:24,749
You're having a baby
and you're wearing that?

178
00:10:24,833 --> 00:10:26,209
Not any more.

179
00:10:26,292 --> 00:10:28,169
This will be as fast as we can.

180
00:10:28,253 --> 00:10:30,213
We'll take the motorway
to the Brooklyn flyover

181
00:10:30,296 --> 00:10:33,216
and then it's gonna take a while
"cause then there's no fast lane,

182
00:10:33,341 --> 00:10:35,009
just ordinary roads,
but at least it's direct.

183
00:10:35,093 --> 00:10:37,470
-It's only 10 miles.
-How long is it gonna take?

184
00:10:37,554 --> 00:10:39,222
About six years.

185
00:10:41,724 --> 00:10:43,309
What?

186
00:10:43,393 --> 00:10:46,229
It'll be just in time for him
to start school.

187
00:10:46,938 --> 00:10:49,774
No, sorry, hold on. Six years?

188
00:10:49,899 --> 00:10:52,360
Ten miles in six years? How come?

189
00:11:03,830 --> 00:11:04,998
(HORN HONKING)

190
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:06,499
(COUGHING)

191
00:11:06,583 --> 00:11:08,501
(CARS HONKING)

192
00:11:21,806 --> 00:11:26,186
Hey! You daft little street strut!
What are you doing standing there?

193
00:11:26,269 --> 00:11:28,938
Either get out or get in. Come on!

194
00:11:33,860 --> 00:11:36,529
-MAN: Did you ever see the like?
-Here you go.

195
00:11:36,613 --> 00:11:39,490
He was just standing there,
breathing it in.

196
00:11:39,574 --> 00:11:43,411
There's this story. It says
back in the old days, on Junction 47,

197
00:11:43,494 --> 00:11:47,373
this woman stood in the exhaust fumes
for a solid 20 minutes.

198
00:11:47,457 --> 00:11:50,585
By the time they found her,
her head had swollen to 50 feet.

199
00:11:50,668 --> 00:11:54,964
-Oh, you're making it up!
-A 50-foot head. Just think of it.

200
00:11:55,048 --> 00:11:58,343
-Imagine picking that nose.
-Oh, stop it. That's disgusting.

201
00:11:58,426 --> 00:12:00,094
What, did you never pick your nose?

202
00:12:00,178 --> 00:12:03,306
-Bran, we're moving.
-Right, I'm there. I'm on it.

203
00:12:06,184 --> 00:12:07,894
(HORNS BLARING)

204
00:12:12,148 --> 00:12:15,276
Twenty yards. We're having a good day.

205
00:12:15,360 --> 00:12:18,238
And who might you be, sir?
Very well dressed for a hitchhiker.

206
00:12:18,321 --> 00:12:20,365
Thanks. Sorry, I'm the Doctor.

207
00:12:20,448 --> 00:12:24,118
Medical man?
My name's Thomas Kincade Brannigan,

208
00:12:24,202 --> 00:12:26,663
and this is the bane of my life,
the lovely Valerie.

209
00:12:26,746 --> 00:12:27,830
Nice to meet you.

210
00:12:27,914 --> 00:12:30,917
And that's the rest of
the family behind you.

211
00:12:33,461 --> 00:12:35,171
Oh, that's nice.

212
00:12:35,296 --> 00:12:36,839
(MEOWING)

213
00:12:37,674 --> 00:12:39,342
Hello.

214
00:12:41,761 --> 00:12:44,180
-How old are they?
-Just two months.

215
00:12:44,305 --> 00:12:48,351
Poor little souls. They've never known
the ground beneath their paws.

216
00:12:48,476 --> 00:12:50,353
Children of the motorway.

217
00:12:50,436 --> 00:12:53,356
-What, they were born in here?
-We couldn't stop.

218
00:12:53,439 --> 00:12:56,776
We heard there were jobs going,
out in the laundries on Fire Island.

219
00:12:56,859 --> 00:13:00,196
-Thought we'd take a chance.
-You've been driving for two months?

220
00:13:00,280 --> 00:13:04,367
Do I look like a teenager?
We've been driving for 12 years now.

221
00:13:04,492 --> 00:13:05,535
Sorry?

222
00:13:05,618 --> 00:13:08,871
Yeah, started out as newlyweds.
Feels like yesterday.

223
00:13:08,997 --> 00:13:12,750
-Feels like 12 years to me.
-Ah, sweetheart, but you still love me.

224
00:13:12,875 --> 00:13:15,336
Twelve years? How far did you come?
Where did you start?

225
00:13:15,420 --> 00:13:17,588
Battery Park. It's five miles back.

226
00:13:17,714 --> 00:13:20,258
You travelled five miles in 12 years?

227
00:13:20,383 --> 00:13:22,385
I think he's a bit slow.

228
00:13:23,219 --> 00:13:26,556
-Where are you from?
-Never mind that. I've got to get out!

229
00:13:26,681 --> 00:13:28,808
My friend's in one of these cars.
She was taken hostage.

230
00:13:28,891 --> 00:13:31,102
I should get back to the Tardis.

231
00:13:31,185 --> 00:13:34,772
You're too late for that.
We've passed the lay-by.

232
00:13:34,897 --> 00:13:37,108
You're a passenger now, sonny Jim.

233
00:13:37,233 --> 00:13:40,945
-When's the next lay-by?
-Oh, six months.

234
00:13:43,573 --> 00:13:45,658
(HORNS BLARING)

235
00:13:48,745 --> 00:13:52,540
-How many cars are out there?
-I don't think anyone knows.

236
00:13:53,207 --> 00:13:55,251
Here we go. Hungry?

237
00:13:55,960 --> 00:13:57,420
Oh, thanks.

238
00:13:58,254 --> 00:14:00,715
How far down is it to this fast lane?

239
00:14:00,798 --> 00:14:03,009
It's right at the bottom,
underneath the traffic jam.

240
00:14:03,092 --> 00:14:06,763
Not many people can afford three
passengers, so it's empty down there.

241
00:14:06,846 --> 00:14:09,515
Rumour has it
you can reach up to 30 miles per hour.

242
00:14:09,599 --> 00:14:11,726
Wow, that's like, crazy.

243
00:14:12,435 --> 00:14:15,271
But how are you supposed to
live inside this thing? It's tiny!

244
00:14:15,396 --> 00:14:17,023
Oh, we stocked up.

245
00:14:17,106 --> 00:14:20,610
We've got self-replicating fuel,
muscle stimulants for exercise,

246
00:14:20,693 --> 00:14:22,445
there's a chemical toilet at the back

247
00:14:22,570 --> 00:14:25,656
and all waste products
are recycled as food.

248
00:14:26,783 --> 00:14:28,034
Okay.

249
00:14:28,117 --> 00:14:30,244
Oh, now, a gap. This is brilliant!

250
00:14:30,328 --> 00:14:34,624
Car 4-6-5-Diamond-6 on descent to
fast lane. Thank you very much.

251
00:14:37,710 --> 00:14:39,629
I need to talk to the police.

252
00:14:39,712 --> 00:14:42,965
Thank you for your call.
You have been placed on hold.

253
00:14:43,091 --> 00:14:44,467
You're the police!

254
00:14:44,550 --> 00:14:48,137
Thank you for your call.
You have been placed on hold.

255
00:14:48,805 --> 00:14:50,973
Is there anyone else?
I once met the Duke of Manhattan.

256
00:14:51,099 --> 00:14:52,767
Is there any way of
getting through to him?

257
00:14:52,850 --> 00:14:55,353
-Oh, now, ain't you lordly?
-I've got to find my friend!

258
00:14:55,478 --> 00:14:59,107
You can't make outside calls.
The motorway's completely enclosed.

259
00:14:59,190 --> 00:15:00,316
What about the other cars?

260
00:15:00,400 --> 00:15:02,902
We've got contact with them, yeah.
Well, some of them anyway.

261
00:15:03,027 --> 00:15:06,114
They've got to be on your friends' list.
Now, let's see, who's near by?

262
00:15:06,197 --> 00:15:08,282
Ah, the Cassini sisters!

263
00:15:09,158 --> 00:15:12,578
Be still your hearts, my handsome girls.
It's Brannigan here.

264
00:15:12,662 --> 00:15:16,249
Get off the line, Brannigan.
You're a pest and a menace.

265
00:15:16,332 --> 00:15:20,002
Come on now, sisters, is that any way
to talk to an old friend?

266
00:15:20,086 --> 00:15:23,673
You know full well we're not sisters.
We're married.

267
00:15:23,798 --> 00:15:27,260
Ooh! Stop that modern talk,
I'm an old-fashioned cat.

268
00:15:27,343 --> 00:15:31,597
Now, I've got a hitchhiker here,
calls himself the Doctor.

269
00:15:31,681 --> 00:15:33,766
Hello. Sorry, I'm looking for someone
called Martha Jones.

270
00:15:33,850 --> 00:15:35,309
She's been carjacked.

271
00:15:35,393 --> 00:15:37,645
She's inside one of these vehicles,
but I don't know which one.

272
00:15:37,728 --> 00:15:39,397
Wait a minute.

273
00:15:40,857 --> 00:15:43,943
Could I ask what entrance did they use?

274
00:15:44,026 --> 00:15:45,528
-Where were we?
-Pharmacy Town.

275
00:15:45,653 --> 00:15:47,447
Pharmacy Town, about 20 minutes ago.

276
00:15:47,530 --> 00:15:49,615
Let's have a look.

277
00:15:49,699 --> 00:15:52,285
Just my luck to marry a car-spotter.

278
00:15:52,368 --> 00:15:54,203
In the last half hour,

279
00:15:54,287 --> 00:15:58,499
53 new cars joined from
the Pharmacy Town junction.

280
00:15:58,583 --> 00:16:00,626
Anything more specific?

281
00:16:00,710 --> 00:16:02,753
All in good time.

282
00:16:02,879 --> 00:16:06,257
-Was she carjacked by two people?
-Yes, she was. Yeah.

283
00:16:06,340 --> 00:16:10,261
There we are! Just one of those cars
was destined for the fast lane.

284
00:16:10,344 --> 00:16:12,555
That means they had three on board.

285
00:16:12,638 --> 00:16:16,058
And the car number is 4-6-5-Diamond-6.

286
00:16:16,142 --> 00:16:17,685
That's it! So how do we find them?

287
00:16:17,768 --> 00:16:20,480
Ah. Now there I'm afraid I can't help.

288
00:16:20,563 --> 00:16:23,024
We can call them on this thing.
We've got their number, Diamond-6.

289
00:16:23,107 --> 00:16:26,194
Not if they're designated fast lane.
It's a different class.

290
00:16:26,277 --> 00:16:29,780
-You could try the police.
-They put me on hold.

291
00:16:29,864 --> 00:16:33,117
You'll have to keep trying.
There's no one else.

292
00:16:33,951 --> 00:16:35,328
Thank you.

293
00:16:37,163 --> 00:16:39,373
(ALL HONKING)

294
00:16:43,419 --> 00:16:47,006
See? Another ten layers to go,
and we're scorching.

295
00:16:47,089 --> 00:16:49,425
(RUMBLING)

296
00:16:51,928 --> 00:16:53,221
What's that?

297
00:16:54,263 --> 00:16:55,890
It's coming from underneath.

298
00:16:55,973 --> 00:16:59,769
It's that noise, isn't it? It's like
Kate said, the stories, they're true!

299
00:16:59,852 --> 00:17:01,062
What stories?

300
00:17:01,145 --> 00:17:03,105
It's the sound of the air vents,
that's all.

301
00:17:03,189 --> 00:17:04,524
Exhaust fumes travel down,

302
00:17:04,607 --> 00:17:06,609
so at the base of the tunnel
they've got air vents.

303
00:17:06,692 --> 00:17:08,778
No, but the stories are much better.

304
00:17:08,861 --> 00:17:11,989
They say people go missing
on the motorway.

305
00:17:12,114 --> 00:17:15,159
Some cars just vanish,
never to be seen again,

306
00:17:15,284 --> 00:17:18,913
'cause there's something
living down there in the smoke.

307
00:17:19,747 --> 00:17:21,874
Something huge

308
00:17:22,416 --> 00:17:24,085
and hungry.

309
00:17:24,794 --> 00:17:28,339
And if you get lost on the road,
it's waiting for you.

310
00:17:30,258 --> 00:17:32,593
(SNARLING)

311
00:17:34,178 --> 00:17:36,681
Well, like I said, air vents.

312
00:17:37,557 --> 00:17:39,976
Going down to the next layer.

313
00:17:40,059 --> 00:17:44,438
Except, look out there. Does it look
like the air vents are working?

314
00:17:44,522 --> 00:17:45,815
No.

315
00:17:46,983 --> 00:17:48,651
(GROWLING)

316
00:17:50,486 --> 00:17:52,572
So what's that, then?

317
00:17:54,574 --> 00:17:56,659
Nah, kids' stuff.

318
00:17:57,493 --> 00:17:59,912
Car 4-6-5-Diamond-6, on descent.

319
00:17:59,996 --> 00:18:02,039
We've got to go to the fast lane.
Take me down.

320
00:18:02,123 --> 00:18:03,708
Not in a million years.

321
00:18:03,791 --> 00:18:06,544
-You've got three passengers.
-I'm still not going.

322
00:18:06,627 --> 00:18:08,421
She's alone and she's lost.

323
00:18:08,504 --> 00:18:11,716
She doesn't even belong on this planet,
and it's all my fault.

324
00:18:11,799 --> 00:18:13,426
I'm asking you, Brannigan, take me down.

325
00:18:13,509 --> 00:18:16,387
That's a no, and that's final.

326
00:18:16,470 --> 00:18:19,056
I'm not risking the children down there.

327
00:18:19,140 --> 00:18:20,975
Why not? What's the risk?
What happens down there?

328
00:18:21,058 --> 00:18:24,520
We're not discussing it.
The conversation is closed.

329
00:18:25,187 --> 00:18:27,189
-So we keep on driving?
-Yes, we do.

330
00:18:27,273 --> 00:18:30,109
-For how long?
-Till the journey's end.

331
00:18:32,695 --> 00:18:34,488
Mrs Cassini, this is the Doctor.

332
00:18:34,572 --> 00:18:36,657
Tell me, how long have you been driving
on the motorway?

333
00:18:36,741 --> 00:18:38,492
Oh, we were amongst the first.

334
00:18:38,576 --> 00:18:41,162
It's been 23 years now.

335
00:18:41,245 --> 00:18:44,874
And in all that time,
have you ever seen a police car?

336
00:18:48,169 --> 00:18:49,670
I'm not sure.

337
00:18:50,713 --> 00:18:53,049
Look at your notes. Any police?

338
00:18:55,343 --> 00:18:58,137
-Not as such.
-Or an ambulance?

339
00:18:58,220 --> 00:19:01,182
Rescue service? Anything official, ever?

340
00:19:01,265 --> 00:19:03,517
I can't keep a note of everything.

341
00:19:03,601 --> 00:19:05,353
What if there's no one out there?

342
00:19:05,436 --> 00:19:08,522
Stop it.
The Cassinis were doing you a favour.

343
00:19:08,606 --> 00:19:12,193
Someone's got to ask, 'cause you
might not talk about it, but it's there,

344
00:19:12,318 --> 00:19:13,944
in your eyes.

345
00:19:14,904 --> 00:19:17,448
What if the traffic jam never stops?

346
00:19:17,573 --> 00:19:21,327
There's a whole city above us.
The mighty city-state of New New York.

347
00:19:21,410 --> 00:19:25,206
-They wouldn't just leave us.
-In that case, where are they? Hmm?

348
00:19:26,749 --> 00:19:29,835
What if there's no help coming,
not ever?

349
00:19:29,919 --> 00:19:31,921
What if there's nothing?

350
00:19:32,046 --> 00:19:34,006
Just the motorway?

351
00:19:34,090 --> 00:19:38,636
With the cars going round and round
and round, never stopping? Forever!

352
00:19:38,761 --> 00:19:41,263
Shut up! Just shut up!

353
00:19:41,722 --> 00:19:44,100
This is Sally Calypso,

354
00:19:44,183 --> 00:19:46,394
and it's that time again.

355
00:19:46,519 --> 00:19:50,272
The sun is blazing high in the sky
over the New Atlantic.

356
00:19:50,356 --> 00:19:52,858
The perfect setting for
the daily contemplation.

357
00:19:52,942 --> 00:19:55,653
You think you know us so well, Doctor.

358
00:19:55,778 --> 00:19:58,989
We are not abandoned.
Not while we have each other.

359
00:19:59,115 --> 00:20:01,617
This is for all of you
out there on the roads.

360
00:20:01,701 --> 00:20:03,369
We're so sorry.

361
00:20:04,120 --> 00:20:05,496
Drive safe.

362
00:20:05,621 --> 00:20:07,998
(OLD RUGGED CROSS PLAYING ON TV MONITOR)

363
00:20:08,124 --> 00:20:10,710
# On a hill far away

364
00:20:10,793 --> 00:20:16,132
# Stood an old rugged cross

365
00:20:16,424 --> 00:20:23,681
# The emblem of suffering and shame

366
00:20:26,642 --> 00:20:31,647
ALL: # And I love that old cross

367
00:20:32,022 --> 00:20:36,736
# Where the dearest and best

368
00:20:37,069 --> 00:20:44,285
# For a world of lost sinners was slain

369
00:20:46,996 --> 00:20:53,878
# So I'll cherish the old rugged cross

370
00:20:53,961 --> 00:20:57,298
# Rugged cross

371
00:20:57,423 --> 00:21:04,847
# Till my trophies at last I lay down

372
00:21:06,974 --> 00:21:13,689
# I will cling to the old rugged cross

373
00:21:13,814 --> 00:21:16,192
# Rugged cross

374
00:21:16,817 --> 00:21:24,074
# And exchange it some day for a crown #

375
00:21:32,792 --> 00:21:35,544
Fast lane access. Please drive safely.

376
00:21:35,628 --> 00:21:38,380
We made it. The fast lane.

377
00:21:48,265 --> 00:21:51,268
If you won't take me,
I'll go there on my own.

378
00:21:51,393 --> 00:21:53,771
What do you think you're doing?

379
00:21:53,896 --> 00:21:56,106
Finding my own way. I usually do.

380
00:21:56,232 --> 00:21:59,109
ELECTRONIC VOICE: Capsule open.

381
00:22:02,112 --> 00:22:03,614
Here we go.

382
00:22:06,951 --> 00:22:09,203
Look after this.

383
00:22:09,286 --> 00:22:12,706
I love that coat.
Janis Joplin gave me that coat.

384
00:22:12,790 --> 00:22:14,458
But you can't jump!

385
00:22:14,542 --> 00:22:17,837
If it's any consolation, Valerie,
right now I'm having kittens.

386
00:22:17,920 --> 00:22:21,465
This Martha,
she must mean an awful lot to you.

387
00:22:21,590 --> 00:22:23,425
Hardly know her.

388
00:22:23,509 --> 00:22:25,678
I was too busy showing off.

389
00:22:26,470 --> 00:22:28,889
And I lied to her.

390
00:22:28,973 --> 00:22:31,308
I couldn't help it, just lied.

391
00:22:31,892 --> 00:22:33,227
Bye, then!

392
00:22:41,235 --> 00:22:43,779
He's completely insane!

393
00:22:43,863 --> 00:22:46,615
That, and a bit magnificent!

394
00:22:49,285 --> 00:22:51,745
Capsule open.

395
00:22:51,829 --> 00:22:53,122
Who the hell are you?

396
00:22:53,205 --> 00:22:55,416
Sorry, motorway foot patrol.
I'm doing a survey.

397
00:22:55,499 --> 00:22:57,042
How are you enjoying your motorway?

398
00:22:57,126 --> 00:23:00,588
Well, not very much. Junction 5's
been closed for three years.

399
00:23:00,671 --> 00:23:03,549
Thank you, your comments
have been noted. Have a nice day!

400
00:23:15,144 --> 00:23:16,812
Capsule open.

401
00:23:20,399 --> 00:23:21,859
Capsule open.

402
00:23:21,942 --> 00:23:24,653
Thank you for your cooperation.
Your comments have been noted.

403
00:23:24,737 --> 00:23:28,449
Do you mind if I borrow this?
Not my colour, but thank you very much!

404
00:23:31,827 --> 00:23:33,662
Capsule open.

405
00:23:33,829 --> 00:23:35,539
Oh, don't mind me.

406
00:23:40,586 --> 00:23:42,212
Capsule open.

407
00:23:45,341 --> 00:23:46,800
Capsule open.

408
00:23:52,222 --> 00:23:53,682
Try again.

409
00:23:53,766 --> 00:23:55,768
Brooklyn turn off 1, closed.

410
00:23:55,851 --> 00:23:57,269
Try the next one.

411
00:23:57,353 --> 00:23:59,563
Brooklyn turn off 2, closed.

412
00:23:59,647 --> 00:24:01,273
What do we do?

413
00:24:01,357 --> 00:24:03,108
We keep going round,
we'll do the whole loop,

414
00:24:03,192 --> 00:24:05,444
by the time we come back round,
they'll be open.

415
00:24:05,527 --> 00:24:07,655
(GROWLING)

416
00:24:09,156 --> 00:24:11,575
You still calling that air vents?

417
00:24:11,659 --> 00:24:13,535
What else could it be?

418
00:24:16,497 --> 00:24:18,624
(GROWLING)

419
00:24:18,707 --> 00:24:21,627
-What the hell is that?
-It's just the hydraulics.

420
00:24:21,710 --> 00:24:23,629
Sounds like it's alive!

421
00:24:23,712 --> 00:24:26,298
It's all exhaust fumes out there.
Nothing could breathe in that.

422
00:24:26,382 --> 00:24:30,260
WOMAN: Calling car 4-6-5-Diamond-6.
Repeat, calling car 4-6-5-Diamond-6.

423
00:24:30,344 --> 00:24:32,262
This is 4-6-5-Diamond-6.
Who's that? Where are you?

424
00:24:32,346 --> 00:24:34,848
I'm in the fast lane,
about 50 yards behind.

425
00:24:34,932 --> 00:24:37,559
Can you get back up?
Can you get off the fast lane?

426
00:24:37,643 --> 00:24:40,270
We only have permission to go down.
We need the Brooklyn Flyover.

427
00:24:40,354 --> 00:24:43,482
-It's closed. Go back up.
-We can't. We'll just go round.

428
00:24:43,565 --> 00:24:46,610
Don't you understand?
They're closed, they're always closed.

429
00:24:46,694 --> 00:24:49,905
We're stuck down here. There's
something else out there in the fog.

430
00:24:49,989 --> 00:24:51,240
Can't you hear it?

431
00:24:51,323 --> 00:24:52,574
(ROARING)

432
00:24:52,658 --> 00:24:56,620
-That's the air vents.
-Jehovah, what are you, some stupid kid?

433
00:24:56,704 --> 00:24:58,789
Get out of here!

434
00:24:59,540 --> 00:25:01,583
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

435
00:25:01,709 --> 00:25:02,876
What was that?

436
00:25:04,294 --> 00:25:06,672
We can't move. It got us.

437
00:25:06,755 --> 00:25:08,924
-What's happening?
-What's got you? What is it?

438
00:25:09,008 --> 00:25:10,300
I don't know...

439
00:25:10,384 --> 00:25:11,802
(ROARING)

440
00:25:11,885 --> 00:25:12,928
(SCREAMING)

441
00:25:13,053 --> 00:25:14,888
-Hello?
-Just drive, you idiots!

442
00:25:14,972 --> 00:25:16,348
Get out of here!

443
00:25:16,432 --> 00:25:18,434
-No/
-Can you hear me? Hello?

444
00:25:18,517 --> 00:25:20,728
Just drive! Do what she said,
get us out of here!

445
00:25:20,811 --> 00:25:23,772
-But where?
-Just straight ahead! And fast!

446
00:25:24,440 --> 00:25:27,776
What is it? What's out there?
What's happening?

447
00:25:30,070 --> 00:25:32,448
Capsule open.

448
00:25:32,531 --> 00:25:34,658
Excuse me! Is that legal?

449
00:25:34,742 --> 00:25:37,202
Sorry, motorway foot patrol.

450
00:25:37,786 --> 00:25:39,413
Whatever. Have you got any water?

451
00:25:39,496 --> 00:25:43,083
Certainly. Never let it be said
I've lost my manners.

452
00:25:46,587 --> 00:25:47,880
Is this the last layer?

453
00:25:47,963 --> 00:25:50,382
We're right at the bottom.
Nothing below us but the fast lane.

454
00:25:50,466 --> 00:25:52,342
-Can we drive down?
-There's only two of us.

455
00:25:52,468 --> 00:25:54,261
-You need three to go down.
-Couldn't we cheat?

456
00:25:54,344 --> 00:25:58,348
I'd love to, but it's an automated
system. The wheel would lock.

457
00:25:58,432 --> 00:26:00,142
Then excuse me.

458
00:26:00,976 --> 00:26:03,187
You can't jump, it's 1,000 feet down!

459
00:26:03,270 --> 00:26:04,855
No, I just want a look.

460
00:26:04,938 --> 00:26:06,190
(ROARING)

461
00:26:06,315 --> 00:26:08,442
What's that noise?

462
00:26:08,525 --> 00:26:11,070
I try not to think about it.

463
00:26:12,321 --> 00:26:15,365
What are those lights?
What's down there?

464
00:26:20,079 --> 00:26:21,914
I just need to see.

465
00:26:22,998 --> 00:26:25,167
There must be some sort of ventilation.

466
00:26:25,250 --> 00:26:28,587
If I could just transmit a pulse through
this thing, I could trip the system.

467
00:26:28,670 --> 00:26:31,340
Give us a bit of a breeze.

468
00:26:31,423 --> 00:26:33,759
(DRILLING)

469
00:26:33,842 --> 00:26:36,345
Just what we need! Pirates!

470
00:26:36,428 --> 00:26:38,430
I'm calling the police!

471
00:26:40,516 --> 00:26:42,518
The Doctor, where is he?

472
00:26:45,020 --> 00:26:48,774
That's it! Might shift the fumes a bit,
give us a good look.

473
00:26:49,441 --> 00:26:50,943
(SCREECHING)

474
00:26:51,527 --> 00:26:53,445
What are those shapes?

475
00:26:54,488 --> 00:26:56,031
They're alive.

476
00:26:57,533 --> 00:26:59,493
What the hell are they?

477
00:27:04,873 --> 00:27:06,458
Macra.

478
00:27:11,880 --> 00:27:14,383
-Go faster!
-I'm at full speed!

479
00:27:19,221 --> 00:27:21,140
No access above.

480
00:27:21,223 --> 00:27:23,308
But this is an emergency!

481
00:27:25,435 --> 00:27:28,647
Thank you for your call.
You have been placed on hold.

482
00:27:31,817 --> 00:27:33,819
-Turn everything off!
-You've got to be joking!

483
00:27:33,902 --> 00:27:36,405
Listen, it's all fog out there,
so how can they see us?

484
00:27:36,572 --> 00:27:40,784
Maybe it's the engine, the sound,
or the heat or the light, I don't know.

485
00:27:40,868 --> 00:27:43,328
But if you turn everything off,
they might not be able to find us.

486
00:27:43,412 --> 00:27:45,247
What if you're wrong?

487
00:27:49,084 --> 00:27:51,420
It can't be worse than this. Just do it!

488
00:27:56,800 --> 00:27:59,803
(MACRA RETREATING)

489
00:28:16,737 --> 00:28:18,739
CHEEN: They've stopped.

490
00:28:19,281 --> 00:28:21,867
Yeah, but they're still out there.

491
00:28:23,368 --> 00:28:25,412
How did you think of that?

492
00:28:25,495 --> 00:28:27,873
I saw it in a film.

493
00:28:27,956 --> 00:28:30,584
They used to do it in submarines.

494
00:28:30,667 --> 00:28:34,004
Trouble is,
I can't remember what they did next.

495
00:28:34,087 --> 00:28:36,757
Well, you'd better think of something,
"cause we've lost the air-con.

496
00:28:36,840 --> 00:28:39,593
If we don't switch the engines back on,
we won't be able to breathe.

497
00:28:39,676 --> 00:28:41,637
How long have we got?

498
00:28:41,720 --> 00:28:43,597
Eight minutes maximum.

499
00:28:48,352 --> 00:28:51,813
The Macra used to be
the scourge of this galaxy. Gas.

500
00:28:51,897 --> 00:28:54,566
They fed off gas.
The filthier, the better.

501
00:28:54,650 --> 00:28:56,902
They built up a small empire
using humans as slaves

502
00:28:56,985 --> 00:28:58,403
and mining gas for food.

503
00:28:58,487 --> 00:29:01,323
They don't exactly
look like empire-builders to me.

504
00:29:01,406 --> 00:29:04,117
Well, that was billions of years ago.

505
00:29:04,201 --> 00:29:08,497
Billions. They must have devolved
down the years. Now they're just beasts.

506
00:29:08,664 --> 00:29:11,041
But they're still hungry,
and my friend's down there.

507
00:29:11,166 --> 00:29:12,793
(BANGING)

508
00:29:12,876 --> 00:29:16,421
It's like New Times Square in here!
For goodness sake!

509
00:29:16,505 --> 00:29:18,757
DOCTOR: I've invented a sport!

510
00:29:18,840 --> 00:29:21,093
Doctor! You're a hard man to find.

511
00:29:21,176 --> 00:29:22,928
No guns! I'm not having guns!

512
00:29:23,011 --> 00:29:25,180
I only brought this in case of pirates.

513
00:29:25,264 --> 00:29:28,558
-Doctor, you've got to come with me.
-Do I know you?

514
00:29:29,643 --> 00:29:31,853
You haven't aged at all.

515
00:29:31,937 --> 00:29:34,314
Time has been less kind to me.

516
00:29:35,399 --> 00:29:36,942
Novice Hame!

517
00:29:37,067 --> 00:29:39,069
Whoa, hold on. Get off!

518
00:29:39,152 --> 00:29:41,613
Last time we met, you were
breeding humans for experimentation.

519
00:29:41,697 --> 00:29:43,824
I've sought forgiveness, Doctor,

520
00:29:43,907 --> 00:29:47,286
for so many years under his guidance.

521
00:29:47,369 --> 00:29:50,706
And if you come with me, I might
finally be able to redeem myself.

522
00:29:50,831 --> 00:29:53,959
I'm not going anywhere. You've got Macra
living underneath this city. Macra!

523
00:29:54,042 --> 00:29:55,877
If my friend's still alive,
she's stuck down there!

524
00:29:55,961 --> 00:29:57,879
You've got to come with me right now!

525
00:29:57,963 --> 00:30:00,299
No, you're coming with me.
We've got three passengers now.

526
00:30:00,382 --> 00:30:04,970
I'm sorry, Doctor, but the situation
is even worse than you can imagine.

527
00:30:05,345 --> 00:30:08,348
-Transport.
-Don't you dare! Don't you dare!

528
00:30:12,019 --> 00:30:13,729
(DOCTOR GROANING)

529
00:30:14,646 --> 00:30:16,857
Rough teleport. Ow!

530
00:30:16,940 --> 00:30:19,234
You can go straight back down
and teleport people out,

531
00:30:19,318 --> 00:30:22,237
-starting with Martha!
-I only had the power for one trip.

532
00:30:22,321 --> 00:30:24,156
Then get some more! Where are we?

533
00:30:24,239 --> 00:30:26,867
High above, in the Overcity.

534
00:30:26,950 --> 00:30:30,162
Good, 'cause you can tell the senate
of New New York I'd like a word.

535
00:30:30,245 --> 00:30:33,332
They have got thousands of people
trapped on the motorway! Millions!

536
00:30:33,415 --> 00:30:36,418
But you're inside the senate, right now.

537
00:30:37,461 --> 00:30:40,047
May the goddess Santori bless thee.

538
00:30:45,177 --> 00:30:46,928
They died, Doctor.

539
00:30:48,138 --> 00:30:50,015
The city died.

540
00:30:51,266 --> 00:30:53,060
How long has it been like this?

541
00:30:53,143 --> 00:30:54,853
24 years.

542
00:31:02,277 --> 00:31:04,863
All of them? Everyone? What happened?

543
00:31:04,946 --> 00:31:07,866
A new chemical. A new mood.

544
00:31:08,742 --> 00:31:11,119
They called it "bliss".

545
00:31:11,203 --> 00:31:13,997
Everyone tried it. They couldn't stop.

546
00:31:14,623 --> 00:31:19,252
A virus mutated
inside the compound and became airborne.

547
00:31:19,836 --> 00:31:23,173
Everything perished.
Even the virus in the end.

548
00:31:25,092 --> 00:31:28,303
It killed the world
in seven minutes flat.

549
00:31:28,387 --> 00:31:31,765
There was just enough time to close down
the walkways and the flyovers,

550
00:31:31,848 --> 00:31:34,017
sealing off the Undercity.

551
00:31:34,559 --> 00:31:38,021
Those people on the motorway
aren't lost, Doctor.

552
00:31:38,105 --> 00:31:39,606
They were saved.

553
00:31:39,689 --> 00:31:41,817
So the whole thing down there
is running on automatic.

554
00:31:41,900 --> 00:31:43,735
There's not enough power
to get them out.

555
00:31:43,819 --> 00:31:46,488
We did all we could
to stop the system from choking.

556
00:31:46,655 --> 00:31:48,824
Who's we? How did you survive?

557
00:31:48,949 --> 00:31:51,284
He protected me.

558
00:31:51,368 --> 00:31:55,539
And he has waited for you
these long years.

559
00:31:55,664 --> 00:31:57,833
Doctor.

560
00:32:01,837 --> 00:32:03,505
The Face of Boe!

561
00:32:04,172 --> 00:32:06,383
I knew you would come.

562
00:32:07,426 --> 00:32:11,138
Back in the old days,
I was made his nurse

563
00:32:11,221 --> 00:32:13,181
as penance for my sin.

564
00:32:13,306 --> 00:32:15,434
Old friend, what happened to you?

565
00:32:15,517 --> 00:32:17,352
A failing.

566
00:32:17,477 --> 00:32:21,523
He protected me from the virus
by shrouding me in his smoke.

567
00:32:22,107 --> 00:32:25,444
But with no one to maintain it,
the city's power died.

568
00:32:25,527 --> 00:32:28,655
The Undercity would have fallen
into the sea.

569
00:32:29,739 --> 00:32:31,533
So he saved them.

570
00:32:31,616 --> 00:32:35,328
The Face of Boe wired himself
into the mainframe.

571
00:32:35,412 --> 00:32:39,124
He's giving his life force
just to keep things running.

572
00:32:39,207 --> 00:32:41,877
But there are planets out there.
You could have called for help.

573
00:32:42,002 --> 00:32:45,714
The last act of the senate
was to declare New Earth unsafe.

574
00:32:45,797 --> 00:32:48,800
The automatic quarantine
lasts for 100 years.

575
00:32:52,345 --> 00:32:54,848
(THE FACE OF BOE GASPING)

576
00:32:55,432 --> 00:32:57,809
So the two of you stayed here.

577
00:33:00,145 --> 00:33:02,439
On your own for all these years.

578
00:33:02,522 --> 00:33:04,232
We had no choice.

579
00:33:06,985 --> 00:33:08,528
Yes, you did.

580
00:33:10,155 --> 00:33:12,574
Save them, Doctor.

581
00:33:12,908 --> 00:33:15,160
Save them.

582
00:33:21,541 --> 00:33:23,418
How much air is left?

583
00:33:25,504 --> 00:33:27,464
Two minutes.

584
00:33:30,091 --> 00:33:32,219
There's always the Doctor.

585
00:33:32,302 --> 00:33:34,596
That friend of mine.

586
00:33:34,679 --> 00:33:36,806
He might think of something.

587
00:33:36,890 --> 00:33:38,934
Martha, no one's coming.

588
00:33:43,939 --> 00:33:46,066
He looked kind of nice.

589
00:33:46,149 --> 00:33:49,736
-He's a bit more than that.
-Are you and him...

590
00:33:49,819 --> 00:33:52,739
Sometimes I think he likes me,

591
00:33:52,822 --> 00:33:55,951
but sometimes I just think
he needs someone with him.

592
00:33:58,286 --> 00:34:01,206
I never even asked. Where's home?

593
00:34:02,791 --> 00:34:04,584
A long way away.

594
00:34:06,461 --> 00:34:10,257
I didn't really think.
I just followed the Doctor and...

595
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:14,719
They don't even know where I am.

596
00:34:14,803 --> 00:34:17,055
My mum and dad.

597
00:34:17,138 --> 00:34:20,016
If I died here, they'd never know.

598
00:34:22,185 --> 00:34:25,272
So, um, who is he, then? This Doctor?

599
00:34:26,982 --> 00:34:29,067
I don't know.

600
00:34:29,150 --> 00:34:31,152
Well, not really.

601
00:34:31,236 --> 00:34:33,530
There's so much he never says.

602
00:34:34,155 --> 00:34:36,658
But that means that

603
00:34:36,783 --> 00:34:39,411
the only hope right now is

604
00:34:39,494 --> 00:34:41,329
a complete stranger.

605
00:34:44,874 --> 00:34:48,420
-Well, that's no use!
-But it is, though.

606
00:34:48,503 --> 00:34:51,006
Because you haven't seen
the things he can do.

607
00:34:51,089 --> 00:34:54,217
Honestly, just trust me. Both of you.

608
00:34:54,301 --> 00:34:58,221
You've got your faith,
you've got your songs and your hymns,

609
00:34:58,305 --> 00:35:00,348
and I've got the Doctor.

610
00:35:03,935 --> 00:35:05,395
Right.

611
00:35:07,689 --> 00:35:10,150
Systems back online.

612
00:35:13,862 --> 00:35:16,072
-Good luck.
-And you.

613
00:35:17,282 --> 00:35:18,575
(GROWLING)

614
00:35:24,164 --> 00:35:27,417
Car 4-6-5-Diamond-6, it still registers!
That's Martha.

615
00:35:27,500 --> 00:35:31,004
I knew she was good.
Novice Hame, hold that in place.

616
00:35:33,173 --> 00:35:36,468
Take the residual energy, convert it,
feed it through the electricity system.

617
00:35:36,551 --> 00:35:39,888
-But there isn't enough power.
-Oh, you got power! You got me!

618
00:35:39,971 --> 00:35:41,723
I'm brilliant with computers,
just you watch.

619
00:35:41,848 --> 00:35:44,976
Hame, every switch
on that bank up to maximum!

620
00:35:50,148 --> 00:35:53,276
I can't power up the city,
but all the city needs is people.

621
00:35:53,401 --> 00:35:55,487
So what are you going to do?

622
00:35:55,570 --> 00:35:57,155
This!

623
00:35:58,281 --> 00:36:00,742
No, no, no, no, no, no!

624
00:36:16,424 --> 00:36:19,302
The transformers are blocked.
The signal can't get through.

625
00:36:19,427 --> 00:36:22,138
-Doctor.
-Yeah, hold on, not now.

626
00:36:22,222 --> 00:36:24,599
I give you my last...

627
00:36:24,683 --> 00:36:26,434
(GASPING)

628
00:36:30,980 --> 00:36:32,649
Hame, look after him!

629
00:36:32,732 --> 00:36:35,276
Don't you go dying on me,
you big old face.

630
00:36:35,360 --> 00:36:36,653
You've got to see this.

631
00:36:38,113 --> 00:36:40,448
The open road. Ha!

632
00:36:41,783 --> 00:36:44,577
-What in Jehovah was that?
-It's coming from above!

633
00:36:44,661 --> 00:36:46,871
What is it? What's happening?

634
00:36:49,749 --> 00:36:51,209
Hold on, May.

635
00:36:54,629 --> 00:36:56,631
Of all the cats in the kingdom.

636
00:37:00,593 --> 00:37:02,011
What is it?

637
00:37:10,645 --> 00:37:12,063
What is it?

638
00:37:16,609 --> 00:37:17,861
Yes!

639
00:37:19,112 --> 00:37:21,239
It's the sun!

640
00:37:21,322 --> 00:37:23,825
Oh, Brannigan!

641
00:37:24,242 --> 00:37:26,995
Children, it's the sunlight!

642
00:37:28,246 --> 00:37:32,417
Sorry, no Sally Calypso, she was just
a hologram. My name's the Doctor.

643
00:37:32,500 --> 00:37:33,835
He's a magician.

644
00:37:33,918 --> 00:37:36,629
And this is an order. Everyone drive up.

645
00:37:36,713 --> 00:37:38,214
-Right now.
-Is he serious?

646
00:37:38,339 --> 00:37:40,300
I've opened the roof of the motorway.
Come on.

647
00:37:40,383 --> 00:37:43,678
Throttle those engines. Drive up.

648
00:37:43,845 --> 00:37:46,181
All of you, the whole Undercity,
drive up.

649
00:37:46,306 --> 00:37:48,475
-Here we go.
-Drive up. Drive up!

650
00:37:48,558 --> 00:37:50,727
We've got to clear that fast lane.

651
00:37:50,852 --> 00:37:54,147
-Drive up and get out of the way.
-BRANNIGAN: Here we go! Whoo!

652
00:37:54,355 --> 00:37:58,777
Oi! Car 4-6-5-Diamond-6.
Martha! Drive up!

653
00:37:58,860 --> 00:38:01,613
-That's the Doctor!
-We can't go up, we'll hit the lane!

654
00:38:01,696 --> 00:38:03,281
Do as he says. Go up!

655
00:38:03,364 --> 00:38:06,242
DOCTOR: You've got access above.
Now, go!

656
00:38:19,047 --> 00:38:20,590
It's daylight.

657
00:38:21,883 --> 00:38:25,428
Oh, my God, that's the sky.
The real sky!

658
00:38:26,221 --> 00:38:27,806
He did it!

659
00:38:29,224 --> 00:38:31,184
I told you. He did it!

660
00:38:40,026 --> 00:38:44,405
Did I tell you, Doctor, you're
not bad, sir? You're not bad at all.

661
00:38:47,534 --> 00:38:49,536
(BOTH EXCLAIMING)

662
00:38:52,247 --> 00:38:55,542
You keep driving, Brannigan.
All the way up.

663
00:38:55,625 --> 00:38:58,670
'Cause it's here, just waiting for you.

664
00:38:58,753 --> 00:39:02,006
The city of New New York,
and it's yours.

665
00:39:02,090 --> 00:39:04,259
And don't forget, I want that coat back.

666
00:39:04,342 --> 00:39:06,761
I reckon that's a fair bargain, sir.

667
00:39:06,886 --> 00:39:10,265
Car 4-6-5-Diamond-6, I've sent you
a flight path, come to the senate.

668
00:39:10,390 --> 00:39:11,850
MARTHA: On my way!

669
00:39:11,933 --> 00:39:13,977
Quite a while since I saw you,
Martha Jones.

670
00:39:14,060 --> 00:39:15,436
Doctor!

671
00:39:38,626 --> 00:39:40,044
Doctor?

672
00:39:41,796 --> 00:39:43,256
Over here.

673
00:39:43,339 --> 00:39:45,758
Doctor! What happened out there?

674
00:39:48,636 --> 00:39:49,971
What's that?

675
00:39:50,096 --> 00:39:53,474
It's the Face of Boe.
It's all right, come say hello.

676
00:39:53,558 --> 00:39:56,477
And this is Hame. She's a cat.
Don't worry.

677
00:39:58,479 --> 00:40:00,481
He's the one that saved you, not me.

678
00:40:00,648 --> 00:40:03,902
My lord gave his life to save the city.

679
00:40:05,486 --> 00:40:07,572
And now he's dying.

680
00:40:07,697 --> 00:40:11,409
No, don't say that.
Not old Boe, plenty of life left.

681
00:40:11,492 --> 00:40:14,621
It's good to breathe the air once more.

682
00:40:15,705 --> 00:40:17,498
Who is he?

683
00:40:19,542 --> 00:40:21,336
I don't even know.

684
00:40:22,003 --> 00:40:25,715
Legend says the Face of Boe
has lived for billions of years.

685
00:40:26,758 --> 00:40:28,885
Isn't that right?

686
00:40:28,968 --> 00:40:30,845
And you're not about to give up now.

687
00:40:30,970 --> 00:40:34,265
Everything has its time.

688
00:40:34,349 --> 00:40:37,185
You know that old friend,
better than most.

689
00:40:37,268 --> 00:40:40,480
-The legend says more.
-Don't. There's no need for that.

690
00:40:40,563 --> 00:40:44,734
It says that the Face of Boe
will speak his final secret

691
00:40:44,859 --> 00:40:46,027
to a traveller.

692
00:40:46,110 --> 00:40:48,696
Yeah, but not yet.
Who needs secrets, eh?

693
00:40:48,821 --> 00:40:51,407
I have seen so much.

694
00:40:51,532 --> 00:40:54,160
Perhaps too much.

695
00:40:54,577 --> 00:40:57,080
I am the last of my kind,

696
00:40:58,039 --> 00:41:02,585
as you are the last of yours, Doctor.

697
00:41:03,628 --> 00:41:06,005
That's why we have to survive.

698
00:41:07,340 --> 00:41:08,758
Both of us.

699
00:41:10,134 --> 00:41:11,636
Don't go.

700
00:41:11,719 --> 00:41:15,556
I must. But know this, Time Lord.

701
00:41:16,349 --> 00:41:19,727
You are not alone.

702
00:41:36,536 --> 00:41:38,371
(SOBBING)

703
00:42:03,229 --> 00:42:05,231
All closed down.

704
00:42:05,314 --> 00:42:06,774
Happy?

705
00:42:06,858 --> 00:42:08,443
Happy-happy.

706
00:42:09,444 --> 00:42:11,529
New New York can start again.

707
00:42:11,612 --> 00:42:13,573
And they've got Novice Hame.

708
00:42:13,656 --> 00:42:18,244
Just what every city needs, cats
in charge. Come on, time we were off.

709
00:42:18,327 --> 00:42:21,456
But what did he mean, the Face of Boe?

710
00:42:21,539 --> 00:42:22,874
You are not alone?

711
00:42:22,957 --> 00:42:24,751
I don't know.

712
00:42:25,626 --> 00:42:28,629
You've got me. Is that what he meant?

713
00:42:30,631 --> 00:42:32,300
I don't think so.

714
00:42:33,217 --> 00:42:34,635
Sorry.

715
00:42:35,720 --> 00:42:36,888
Then what?

716
00:42:36,971 --> 00:42:40,141
Doesn't matter.
Back to the Tardis, off we go.

717
00:42:46,189 --> 00:42:49,984
-Right, are you staying?
-Till you talk to me properly, yes.

718
00:42:50,109 --> 00:42:52,070
He said, "Last of your kind."
What does that mean?

719
00:42:52,195 --> 00:42:56,824
-It really doesn't matter.
-You don't talk. You never say. Why not?

720
00:42:56,908 --> 00:42:59,744
(CITIZENS SINGING OLD RUGGED CROSS)

721
00:43:03,331 --> 00:43:04,874
It's the city.

722
00:43:08,252 --> 00:43:09,921
They're singing.

723
00:43:26,104 --> 00:43:27,688
I lied to you.

724
00:43:28,481 --> 00:43:30,191
'Cause I liked it.

725
00:43:31,567 --> 00:43:33,361
I could pretend.

726
00:43:34,028 --> 00:43:37,573
Just for a bit,
I could imagine they were still alive.

727
00:43:38,032 --> 00:43:40,368
Underneath a burnt orange sky.

728
00:43:43,246 --> 00:43:45,373
I'm not just a Time Lord.

729
00:43:47,375 --> 00:43:49,752
I'm the last of the Time Lords.

730
00:43:51,712 --> 00:43:54,924
The Face of Boe was wrong,
there's no one else.

731
00:43:55,466 --> 00:43:57,385
What happened?

732
00:44:09,814 --> 00:44:11,774
There was a war.

733
00:44:14,068 --> 00:44:15,570
A Time War.

734
00:44:16,320 --> 00:44:18,322
The last great Time War.

735
00:44:19,282 --> 00:44:22,869
My people fought
a race called the Daleks,

736
00:44:22,952 --> 00:44:26,080
for the sake of all creation,
and they lost.

737
00:44:28,332 --> 00:44:30,793
They lost. Everyone lost.

738
00:44:35,423 --> 00:44:37,300
They're all gone now.

739
00:44:38,217 --> 00:44:39,635
My family.

740
00:44:40,803 --> 00:44:43,306
My friends. Even that sky.

741
00:44:45,516 --> 00:44:48,352
You should have seen it,
that old planet.

742
00:44:52,815 --> 00:44:57,236
The second sun would rise in the south
and the mountains would shine.

743
00:44:59,363 --> 00:45:01,949
The leaves on the trees were silver.

744
00:45:02,909 --> 00:45:05,119
When they caught the light
every morning,

745
00:45:05,203 --> 00:45:07,580
it looked like a forest on fire.

746
00:45:09,332 --> 00:45:11,167
When the autumn came,

747
00:45:11,292 --> 00:45:15,504
a breeze would blow through
the branches. It sounded like a song...

748
00:45:27,642 --> 00:45:30,728
MARTHA: It's the Statue of Liberty.
I've always wanted to go to New York.

749
00:45:30,811 --> 00:45:32,146
(SQUEALING)

750
00:45:32,271 --> 00:45:35,608
It's the Depression, sweetie. Your heart
might break, but the show goes on.

751
00:45:35,691 --> 00:45:37,568
MARTHA: Hooverville mystery deepens.

752
00:45:37,652 --> 00:45:39,487
Arm yourselves. Come on!

753
00:45:39,612 --> 00:45:41,239
MAN 1: Who are we working for?

754
00:45:41,322 --> 00:45:42,907
MAN 2: Behold your masters.

755
00:45:42,990 --> 00:45:44,700
What do you mean, creatures?

756
00:45:44,784 --> 00:45:46,202
(SQUEALING)

757
00:45:46,327 --> 00:45:47,745
-What the hell was that?
-Doctor?

758
00:45:47,828 --> 00:45:49,163
Run!

759
00:45:50,373 --> 00:45:52,667
Hands in the air, and no funny business.

760
00:45:52,750 --> 00:45:54,085
Where's Martha?

761
00:45:54,168 --> 00:45:55,419
(SCREAMING)

762
00:45:55,503 --> 00:45:57,171
It's insane, it's inhuman!

763
00:45:57,505 --> 00:45:59,257
(SHUSHING)

764
00:45:59,382 --> 00:46:02,593
DOCTOR: They always survive,
while I lose everything.

